					</dd>
					<dt class="comment byuser comment-author-admin odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-32628">
<span class="avatar"><a href="http://www.runtogold.com" rel="nofollow"></a></span>
<span class="comment_num"><a href="#comment-32628" title="Permalink to this comment" rel="nofollow">8</a></span>
<span class="comment_author"><a href="http://www.runtogold.com"   rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Trace Mayer, J.D.</a></span>
<span class="comment_time">April 5, 2011 at 9:39 pm</span>

					</dt>
					<dd class="comment byuser comment-author-admin odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
<div class="format_text" id="comment-body-32628">
<p>Richard, those are good questions. Sales taxes will depend on the state you are in. If you order from an out of state dealer like <a href="http://www.runtogold.com/apmexgoldgeneral" rel="nofollow">Apmex</a> then sales tax is likely not due. Some states have odd sales tax laws like California which assesses sales tax only on transactions below $1000, if I remember correctly. There may be capital gains taxes due and they are usually at a 28% rate as a &#8216;collectible&#8217;. But this can be complicated when buying American Silver Eagles because they are &#8216;legal tender&#8217; and there is no intelligible definition in federal law to the issue of What Is A Dollar? This leads to great uncertainty in the law and unpredictability. Another issue is enforceability because of the tremendous <a href="http://www.howtovanish.com/2009/10/the-sweet-sound-of-cash/" rel="nofollow">privacy rights associated with gold and silver</a> which is a reason they stand as an essential check and balance in the political machinery.</p>
</div>
